text:
Analyzing Friends Dialogue

This data was obtained from user EmilHvitfeldt on Github. You can find the link here. I will use the data to analyze how much they mention dating over the years of the show being aired and how viewership varies based on the name of the main character in the title of the episode.


Code
# load packages
library(tidyverse)




Code
# load data sets 
load(file="friendsdata/friends.rda")
load(file="friendsdata/friends_info.rda")




Code
# how many times is the word date, dating, or dated is said per episode depending on the year

basic_info &lt;- friends_info |&gt;
  mutate(year_aired = str_sub(air_date, 1,4))|&gt;
  group_by(year_aired)|&gt;
  mutate(numepyear = n()) |&gt;
  select(season, episode, year_aired, numepyear)

friend_date &lt;- friends |&gt;
  left_join(basic_info, by = c("season", "episode")) |&gt;
  group_by(year_aired) |&gt;
  filter(str_detect(text, "(?i)\\bdate|dating\\b") == TRUE) |&gt;
  summarise(date_ment = n(), numepyear)  |&gt;
  distinct() |&gt;
  mutate(datepeppyear = date_ment/numepyear)

ggplot(friend_date, aes(x = year_aired, y = datepeppyear)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(
    x = "Year Aired",
    y = "Number of times date said per episode",
    title = "Concept of Dating Mentioned Over the Years in Friends Dialogue"
  )





In 1995,1996, 1998, and 1999 the word date was said a lot less often in friends. I have never watched friends but I assume that during these years, the main characters were in more long term relationships. This is probably why we see a dip in 2004 as well because they are wrapping up the show and giving the characters happy endings with a partner. Again this paragraph is written by someone who has never watched friends.


Code
# in the titles how common is it for a main character to get mentioned

main &lt;- friends_info |&gt;
  filter(str_detect(title,"The One") == TRUE) |&gt;
  mutate(title = str_replace(title, "The One ", "The One:")) |&gt;
  mutate(spec_title = str_extract(title, "(?&lt;=:).+"))|&gt;
  mutate(main_char = if_else(str_detect(spec_title, 
                                "(?i)\\bchandler|monica|joey|phoebe|rachel|ross\\b"), str_extract(spec_title, 
                                "(?i)\\bchandler|monica|joey|phoebe|rachel|ross\\b"), "None"))


ggplot(main, aes(fill = main_char, x = main_char, y = us_views_millions)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Main Character in Title",
       y = "Episode Views in millions",
       title = "Friends Episode Viewership Based on Main Character in Title") 





Having some characters names in the title leads to a higher mean of viewers like Monica and Chandler but having Ross’ name in the title leads to a lower mean of viewers. Having the other main characters names in the tile leads to a similar mean value as having no main character name in the title at all. Overall there is a lot of overlap and the differences are not that significant. If I had a show and I wanted to know if putting certain characters names in the titles lead to more views than I would appreciate that knowledge.

The simulation I am running will be about how many schools a medical school applicant is likely to get into. First I am using the data from the 2024 matriculant data from AAMC into US Medical Schools, the data set can be found here. I will be using this to have a list of schools with their state location and the acceptance rate of each school. The first part of the simulation will pick 20 random schools because most applicants usually apply to that many. Then it will pick a number between 0 and 100 if the number is lower than the acceptance rate than it will count how it as them getting into the school.Then I will run a secon similation to see how it differs if someone is from a region and would like to stay in that region. When running this simulation, I made it so that the number was between 0 and 50 because of in-state or same region preferences that some schools have.


Code
library(tidyverse)
library(openxlsx)




Code
# open up the data and calculate acceptance rates
medschool &lt;- read.xlsx("mdsimdata.xlsx", sheet = "Usable") |&gt;
  mutate(acceptrate = matriculants/applicants)

northeast &lt;-("CT|DC|MA|MD|NH|NJ|NY|PA|RI|VT")
south &lt;- ("AL|AR|FL|GA|KY|KS|LA|NC|NE|OK|SC|TN|TX|VA|WV")
west &lt;- ("AZ|CA|CO|HI|NM|NV|OR|UT|WA|WY")
midwest &lt;- ("IA|IL|IN|MI|MO|MN|ND|OH|SD|WI")

reg_medschool &lt;- medschool |&gt;
  mutate(state = str_sub(state, 1,2)) |&gt;
  mutate(region = ifelse(str_detect(state, midwest) , "Midwest",
           ifelse(str_detect(state, south), "South", 
                  ifelse(str_detect(state, west) , "West", "Northeast"
             ))))




Code
accepted &lt;- function(numschools){
  medschool |&gt;
    sample_n(numschools) |&gt;
    mutate(qual = runif(numschools)) |&gt;
    mutate(gotin = ifelse(qual &lt; acceptrate, 1, 0)) |&gt;
    summarize(numaccept = sum(gotin))
}




Code
trials &lt;- rep(c(20), 500)

sim &lt;- map_df(trials, accepted)|&gt;
  rbind() 

ggplot(sim) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = numaccept)) +
  labs(
    x = "Number of Schools Accepted",
    y = "Number of Applicants",
    title = "Amount of Medical Schools Accepted Into When Applying to 20 Schools"
  )





This histogram shows how selective medical schools are and that if you are getting into multiple schools you have to be a really good candidate.


Code
reg_opt &lt;-c("Midwest", "South", "West", "Northeast")

accepted_by_region &lt;- function(numschools){
  reg_select &lt;- sample.int(4, 1)
  reg_medschool |&gt;
    filter(region == reg_opt[reg_select]) |&gt;
    sample_n(size = numschools) |&gt;
    mutate(qual = runif(numschools, min = 0, max = 0.5)) |&gt;
    mutate(gotin = ifelse(qual &lt; acceptrate, 1, 0)) |&gt;
    group_by(region) |&gt;
    summarize(numaccept = sum(gotin))
}




Code
trials &lt;- rep(c(20), 500)

sim &lt;- map_df(trials, accepted_by_region)|&gt;
  rbind() 

ggplot(sim) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = numaccept, fill = region)) +
  labs(
    x = "Number of Schools Accepted",
    y = "Number of Applicants",
    title = "Amount of Medical Schools Accepted Into When Applying to 20 Schools"
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~region)





This histogram makes it seem like schools in the Northeast are more likely to accep people than any other region. It may be helpful to see these graphs represented in proportions to have a more firm stance on how medical school acceptance may differ based on region. This also incorporates a big assumption that being a local to a region makes you a more attractive candidate. Some things I would do to improve my sim in the future is create a function with more variables. The schools would have public or private so then I could do an if else for region preference.
